{{Otheruses||Osaka Prefecture's Ibaraki City river|Ibaraki River}} {{Infobox River | name = Saho River | image = [[File:佐保川の桜１.jpg|300px|Saho River, photographed March 2007]] | image_caption = View of the Saho River from Ōmiya Bridge in Hōren-chō, Nara City, facing Mount Wakakusa | basin_countries = Japan | river_system = {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|12=draft|12=draft}} system | river_type = {{ill|Class A river|ja|一級河川|12=draft|12=draft}} | length = 19 km | source1 = {{ill|Ishikiri Pass|ja|石切峠|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nara Prefecture) | source1_elevation = 460 m | mouth = {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nara Prefecture) | basin_size = 129 km² | discharge1 = -- | region = Nara Prefecture }}
The '''Saho River''' (佐保川, ''Sahogawa'') is a {{ill|Class A river|ja|一級河川|12=draft|12=draft}} and a tributary of the {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|12=draft|12=draft}}. It flows through the northern areas of {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Yamatokōriyama|ja|大和郡山市|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Geography == [[File:川路桜２.jpg|thumb|Cherry blossoms along the riverbanks, said to have been developed during the tenure of {{ill|Kawaji Saneomi|ja|川路聖謨|12=draft|12=draft}} as Nara Magistrate]] [[File:Saho River, Daian-ji, Nara.jpg|thumb|Saho River flowing through Koi-no-Kubo in Nara City during autumn]] The river originates near {{ill|Mount Kasuga Primeval Forest|ja|春日山原始林|12=draft|12=draft}} between Mount Hana and Mount Yoshi, at {{ill|Ishikiri Pass|ja|石切峠|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|12=draft|12=draft}}. It flows around Mount Wakakusa and traverses northern Nara City in a westward direction.<ref name="yamato" /><ref name="seto">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.seto.or.jp/upload/publish/seto_vol_82.pdf|title=Seto Inland Sea|publisher=Seto Inland Sea Environmental Conservation Association|page=66|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref> Near Nara City Hall, it turns southward, passing through Yamatokōriyama before merging with the {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|12=draft|12=draft}} (locally known as the {{ill|Hase River|ja|初瀬川|12=draft|12=draft}}) near the Nara Prefecture Water Purification Center.<ref name="yamato" /> The river has a basin area of 129 km², covering approximately 12% of the Yamato River's basin, with a total length of 19 km.<ref name="seto" />
At its headwaters, the source features a waterfall known as Uguisu Falls, which is 10 meters in height.<ref name="yamato">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.yamato-shinkin.co.jp/news/detail/pdf/pdf_0059.pdf|title=Our Connection to the Yamato River No.9: Saho River|publisher=Yamato Shinkin Bank|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www3.pref.nara.jp/park/secure/2833/kasugayamagenshirin_guide.pdf|title=Guide to Kasuga Primeval Forest|publisher=Nara Prefecture|accessdate=2021-03-01}}</ref>
In ancient times, the Saho River was symbolically associated with the {{ill|Azure Dragon|ja|青龍|12=draft|12=draft}}, which flows to the east of the capital {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京|12=draft|12=draft}}, as per the principles of {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> During the Edo period, the river was celebrated as part of the "Eight Views of Nanto" (南都八景), particularly for its fireflies.<ref name="yamato" />
The midstream section of the river in Nara City is lined with cherry trees on both banks, attracting crowds during the spring hanami season.<ref name="yamato" /> From late March to early April, the "Saho River Kawaji Cherry Blossom Festival" is held between the JR Saho River Bridge and the Funabashi shopping district. However, the traditional lantern-lit "Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival," which had been held for 23 years around the Ōmiya Bridge, ended in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.nara-np.co.jp/news/20230228215824.html|title=End of the 23-Year Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival|publisher=Nara Newspaper|date=2023-03-01}}</ref>
== Municipalities along the River == ; Nara Prefecture : {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamatokōriyama|ja|大和郡山市|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Main Tributaries == * '''Iwai River''': Originates from {{ill|Mount Takamado|ja|高円山|12=draft|12=draft}} near {{ill|Byakugō-ji|ja|白毫寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, merges with Notogawa, and flows into the Saho River in {{ill|Hachijō, Nara|ja|八条|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Akishino River''': Joins the Saho River in {{ill|Kannonji, Yamatokōriyama|ja|観音寺, 大和郡山市|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''{{ill|Bodaiji River|ja|菩提仙川|12=draft|12=draft}}''': Originates from {{ill|Mount Shiro|ja|城山|1=Shiroyama|2=ja|3=城山|4=zh|5=城山|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kitatsubao, Nara|ja|北椿尾|12=draft|12=draft}}, flows through northern {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|12=draft|12=draft}}, and merges into the Saho River at {{ill|Banjō, Yamatokōriyama|ja|番条|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Takase River''': Originates near {{ill|Sakura Pass|ja|桜峠|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Fukuzumi, Tenri|ja|福住|12=draft|12=draft}}, and joins the Saho River at {{ill|Izu, Yamatokōriyama|ja|伊豆七条|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" />
== Cultural Significance == Given its proximity to Nara's historic center, the Saho River has often been featured in Japanese poetry: * ''Treading on the small stones of Saho River / The black horse arrives, / Could it not be New Year already?'' ({{ill|Ōtomo no Sakanoue no Iratsume|ja|大伴坂上郎女|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''{{ill|Man'yōshū|ja|万葉集|12=draft|12=draft}}'') * ''Blocking the Saho River's flow / And planting rice paddies, / The farmer's swift meal—alone he eats.'' (Upper phrase: Nun / Lower phrase: {{ill|Ōtomo no Yakamochi|ja|大伴家持|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Man'yōshū'') * ''Gazing across the Saho River's plain, / Caught in the breeze / Are the strands of green willow.'' ({{ill|Saigyō|ja|西行|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''{{ill|Sankashū|ja|山家集|12=draft|12=draft}}'')
