At its headwaters, the source features a waterfall known as Uguisu Falls, which is 10 meters in height.<ref name="yamato">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.yamato-shinkin.co.jp/news/detail/pdf/pdf_0059.pdf|title=Our Connection to the Yamato River No.9: Saho River|publisher=Yamato Shinkin Bank|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www3.pref.nara.jp/park/secure/2833/kasugayamagenshirin_guide.pdf|title=Guide to Kasuga Primeval Forest|publisher=Nara Prefecture|accessdate=2021-03-01}}</ref>
In ancient times, the Saho River was symbolically associated with the {{ill|Azure Dragon|ja|青龍|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which flows to the east of the capital {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, as per the principles of {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> During the Edo period, the river was celebrated as part of the "Eight Views of Nanto" (南都八景), particularly for its fireflies.<ref name="yamato" />
The midstream section of the river in Nara City is lined with cherry trees on both banks, attracting crowds during the spring hanami season.<ref name="yamato" /> From late March to early April, the "Saho River Kawaji Cherry Blossom Festival" is held between the JR Saho River Bridge and the Funabashi shopping district. However, the traditional lantern-lit "Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival," which had been held for 23 years around the Ōmiya Bridge, ended in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.nara-np.co.jp/news/20230228215824.html|title=End of the 23-Year Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival|publisher=Nara Newspaper|date=2023-03-01}}</ref>
== Municipalities along the River == ; Nara Prefecture : {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yamatokōriyama|ja|大和郡山市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== Main Tributaries == * '''Iwai River''': Originates from {{ill|Mount Takamado|ja|高円山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} near {{ill|Byakugō-ji|ja|白毫寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, merges with Notogawa, and flows into the Saho River in {{ill|Hachijō, Nara|ja|八条|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Akishino River''': Joins the Saho River in {{ill|Kannonji, Yamatokōriyama|ja|観音寺, 大和郡山市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''{{ill|Bodaiji River|ja|菩提仙川|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''': Originates from {{ill|Mount Shiro|ja|城山|1=Shiroyama|2=ja|3=城山|4=zh|5=城山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Kitatsubao, Nara|ja|北椿尾|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, flows through northern {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and merges into the Saho River at {{ill|Banjō, Yamatokōriyama|ja|番条|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Takase River''': Originates near {{ill|Sakura Pass|ja|桜峠|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Fukuzumi, Tenri|ja|福住|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and joins the Saho River at {{ill|Izu, Yamatokōriyama|ja|伊豆七条|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="yamato" />
== Cultural Significance == Given its proximity to Nara's historic center, the Saho River has often been featured in Japanese poetry: * ''Treading on the small stones of Saho River / The black horse arrives, / Could it not be New Year already?'' ({{ill|Ōtomo no Sakanoue no Iratsume|ja|大伴坂上郎女|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''{{ill|Man'yōshū|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'') * ''Blocking the Saho River's flow / And planting rice paddies, / The farmer's swift meal—alone he eats.'' (Upper phrase: Nun / Lower phrase: {{ill|Ōtomo no Yakamochi|ja|大伴家持|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''Man'yōshū'') * ''Gazing across the Saho River's plain, / Caught in the breeze / Are the strands of green willow.'' ({{ill|Saigyō|ja|西行|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''{{ill|Sankashū|ja|山家集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'')
