{{Otheruses||Osaka Prefecture's Ibaraki City river|Ibaraki River}} {{Infobox River | name = Saho River | image = [[File:佐保川の桜１.jpg|300px|Saho River, photographed March 2007]] | image_caption = View of the Saho River from Ōmiya Bridge in Hōren-chō, Nara City, facing Mount Wakakusa | basin_countries = Japan | river_system = {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato River|qq=}} system | river_type = {{ill|Class A river|ja|一級河川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Class A river|qq=}} | length = 19 km | source1 = {{ill|Ishikiri Pass|ja|石切峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikiri Pass|qq=}} (Nara Prefecture) | source1_elevation = 460 m | mouth = {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato River|qq=}} (Nara Prefecture) | basin_size = 129 km² | discharge1 = -- | region = Nara Prefecture }}
The '''Saho River''' (佐保川, ''Sahogawa'') is a {{ill|Class A river|ja|一級河川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Class A river|qq=}} and a tributary of the {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato River|qq=}}. It flows through the northern areas of {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara City|qq=}} and {{ill|Yamatokōriyama|ja|大和郡山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatokōriyama|qq=}} in {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}}.
== Geography == [[File:川路桜２.jpg|thumb|Cherry blossoms along the riverbanks, said to have been developed during the tenure of {{ill|Kawaji Saneomi|ja|川路聖謨|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawaji Saneomi|qq=}} as Nara Magistrate]] [[File:Saho River, Daian-ji, Nara.jpg|thumb|Saho River flowing through Koi-no-Kubo in Nara City during autumn]] The river originates near {{ill|Mount Kasuga Primeval Forest|ja|春日山原始林|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Kasuga Primeval Forest|qq=}} between Mount Hana and Mount Yoshi, at {{ill|Ishikiri Pass|ja|石切峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikiri Pass|qq=}} in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara City|qq=}}. It flows around Mount Wakakusa and traverses northern Nara City in a westward direction.<ref name="yamato" /><ref name="seto">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.seto.or.jp/upload/publish/seto_vol_82.pdf|title=Seto Inland Sea|publisher=Seto Inland Sea Environmental Conservation Association|page=66|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref> Near Nara City Hall, it turns southward, passing through Yamatokōriyama before merging with the {{ill|Yamato River|ja|大和川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato River|qq=}} (locally known as the {{ill|Hase River|ja|初瀬川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase River|qq=}}) near the Nara Prefecture Water Purification Center.<ref name="yamato" /> The river has a basin area of 129 km², covering approximately 12% of the Yamato River's basin, with a total length of 19 km.<ref name="seto" />
At its headwaters, the source features a waterfall known as Uguisu Falls, which is 10 meters in height.<ref name="yamato">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.yamato-shinkin.co.jp/news/detail/pdf/pdf_0059.pdf|title=Our Connection to the Yamato River No.9: Saho River|publisher=Yamato Shinkin Bank|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www3.pref.nara.jp/park/secure/2833/kasugayamagenshirin_guide.pdf|title=Guide to Kasuga Primeval Forest|publisher=Nara Prefecture|accessdate=2021-03-01}}</ref>
In ancient times, the Saho River was symbolically associated with the {{ill|Azure Dragon|ja|青龍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azure Dragon|qq=}}, which flows to the east of the capital {{ill|Heijō-kyō|ja|平城京|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heijō-kyō|qq=}}, as per the principles of {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōdō|qq=}}.<ref name="yamato" /> During the Edo period, the river was celebrated as part of the "Eight Views of Nanto" (南都八景), particularly for its fireflies.<ref name="yamato" />
The midstream section of the river in Nara City is lined with cherry trees on both banks, attracting crowds during the spring hanami season.<ref name="yamato" /> From late March to early April, the "Saho River Kawaji Cherry Blossom Festival" is held between the JR Saho River Bridge and the Funabashi shopping district. However, the traditional lantern-lit "Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival," which had been held for 23 years around the Ōmiya Bridge, ended in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.nara-np.co.jp/news/20230228215824.html|title=End of the 23-Year Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival|publisher=Nara Newspaper|date=2023-03-01}}</ref>
