The '''Saho River''' (佐保川, ''Sahogawa'') is a {{ill|Class A river|ja|一級河川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Class A river|qq=}} and a tributary of the [[:en:Yamato River|Yamato River]]. It flows through the northern areas of [[:en:Nara (city)|Nara City]] and [[:en:Yamatokōriyama|Yamatokōriyama]] in [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]].
== Geography == [[File:川路桜２.jpg|thumb|Cherry blossoms along the riverbanks, said to have been developed during the tenure of {{ill|Kawaji Saneomi|ja|川路聖謨|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawaji Saneomi|qq=}} as Nara Magistrate]] [[File:Saho River, Daian-ji, Nara.jpg|thumb|Saho River flowing through Koi-no-Kubo in Nara City during autumn]] The river originates near [[:en:Kasugayama Primeval Forest|Mount Kasuga Primeval Forest]] between Mount Hana and Mount Yoshi, at {{ill|Ishikiri Pass|ja|石切峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikiri Pass|qq=}} in [[:en:Nara (city)|Nara City]]. It flows around Mount Wakakusa and traverses northern Nara City in a westward direction.<ref name="yamato" /><ref name="seto">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.seto.or.jp/upload/publish/seto_vol_82.pdf|title=Seto Inland Sea|publisher=Seto Inland Sea Environmental Conservation Association|page=66|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref> Near Nara City Hall, it turns southward, passing through Yamatokōriyama before merging with the [[:en:Yamato River|Yamato River]] (locally known as the {{ill|Hase River|ja|初瀬川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase River|qq=}}) near the Nara Prefecture Water Purification Center.<ref name="yamato" /> The river has a basin area of 129 km², covering approximately 12% of the Yamato River's basin, with a total length of 19 km.<ref name="seto" />
At its headwaters, the source features a waterfall known as Uguisu Falls, which is 10 meters in height.<ref name="yamato">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.yamato-shinkin.co.jp/news/detail/pdf/pdf_0059.pdf|title=Our Connection to the Yamato River No.9: Saho River|publisher=Yamato Shinkin Bank|accessdate=2023-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www3.pref.nara.jp/park/secure/2833/kasugayamagenshirin_guide.pdf|title=Guide to Kasuga Primeval Forest|publisher=Nara Prefecture|accessdate=2021-03-01}}</ref>
In ancient times, the Saho River was symbolically associated with the {{ill|Azure Dragon|ja|青龍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Azure Dragon|qq=}}, which flows to the east of the capital [[:en:Heijō-kyō|Heijō-kyō]], as per the principles of [[:en:Onmyōdō|Onmyōdō]].<ref name="yamato" /> During the Edo period, the river was celebrated as part of the "Eight Views of Nanto" (南都八景), particularly for its fireflies.<ref name="yamato" />
The midstream section of the river in Nara City is lined with cherry trees on both banks, attracting crowds during the spring hanami season.<ref name="yamato" /> From late March to early April, the "Saho River Kawaji Cherry Blossom Festival" is held between the JR Saho River Bridge and the Funabashi shopping district. However, the traditional lantern-lit "Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival," which had been held for 23 years around the Ōmiya Bridge, ended in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.nara-np.co.jp/news/20230228215824.html|title=End of the 23-Year Saho River Cherry Blossom Festival|publisher=Nara Newspaper|date=2023-03-01}}</ref>
== Municipalities along the River == ; Nara Prefecture : [[:en:Nara (city)|Nara City]], [[:en:Yamatokōriyama|Yamatokōriyama]]
== Main Tributaries == * '''Iwai River''': Originates from {{ill|Mount Takamado|ja|高円山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Takamado|qq=}} near [[:en:Byakugō-ji|Byakugō-ji]], merges with Notogawa, and flows into the Saho River in [[:en:Hachijō|Hachijō, Nara]].<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Akishino River''': Joins the Saho River in {{ill|Kannonji, Yamatokōriyama|ja|観音寺, 大和郡山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannonji, Yamatokōriyama|qq=}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''{{ill|Bodaiji River|ja|菩提仙川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bodaiji River|qq=}}''': Originates from [[:en:Shiroyama|Shiroyama]] in {{ill|Kitatsubao, Nara|ja|北椿尾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitatsubao, Nara|qq=}}, flows through northern [[:en:Tenri, Nara|Tenri]], and merges into the Saho River at {{ill|Banjō, Yamatokōriyama|ja|番条|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Banjō, Yamatokōriyama|qq=}}.<ref name="yamato" /> * '''Takase River''': Originates near {{ill|Sakura Pass|ja|桜峠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakura Pass|qq=}} in {{ill|Fukuzumi, Tenri|ja|福住|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuzumi, Tenri|qq=}}, and joins the Saho River at {{ill|Izu, Yamatokōriyama|ja|伊豆七条|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izu, Yamatokōriyama|qq=}}.<ref name="yamato" />
== Cultural Significance == Given its proximity to Nara's historic center, the Saho River has often been featured in Japanese poetry: * ''Treading on the small stones of Saho River / The black horse arrives, / Could it not be New Year already?'' ([[:en:Ōtomo no Sakanoue no Iratsume|Ōtomo no Sakanoue no Iratsume]], ''[[:en:Man'yōshū|Man'yōshū]]'') * ''Blocking the Saho River's flow / And planting rice paddies, / The farmer's swift meal—alone he eats.'' (Upper phrase: Nun / Lower phrase: [[:en:Ōtomo no Yakamochi|Ōtomo no Yakamochi]], ''Man'yōshū'') * ''Gazing across the Saho River's plain, / Caught in the breeze / Are the strands of green willow.'' ([[:en:Saigyō|Saigyō]], ''[[:en:Sankashū|Sankashū]]'')
